\section{Sets}
\subsection{Introduction to Sets}

A \textbf{set} is an unordered collection of distinct \textbf{elements}. This means that a set has different entities that make it up, and the order these entities are written in does not change the properties of the set. In this course, we will only be looking at sets containing only numbers, though sets can also contain other types of elements (like letters, words, breakfast foods, etc.) or even other sets.

Sets are demarcated with the curly braces \{ and \}. The
elements of the set are written inside the braces. The set containing the numbers ``\(2\)," ``\(3\)," ``\(5\)", and ``\(7\)" is \(\{2,3,5,7\},\) though writing \(\{3,7,5,2\}\) or \(\{5,3,2,7\}\) or any of the other \(21\) possibilities is also acceptable.

We can use special characters to denote if a number \(n\) is in a set \(S.\) If \(S\) contains \(n,\) then we can write \(n\in S\); otherwise, we write \(n\not\in S.\) A set that contains no elements is known as the \textbf{empty set}, denoted \(\varnothing.\)

We can construct sets that follow certain rules with \(n|C(n)\) notation. \(C(n)\) is the condition a number \(n\) has to follow to be in set \(S.\) For the above set, possible rules could be \(S=\{n|\text{primes less than }10\}\) or \(S=\{x|\text{solutions to the equation }x^4-17x^3+101x^2-247x+210=0\}\) or many other things. 

If we describe all \(x\) that satisfy a given condition, then we use the character \(\Forall,\) meaning ``for all". To demonstrate, we can say \(x^2>0\Forall x\in\{-1,3,28\},\) but \(\{x|x^2<0\}=\varnothing.\)

\subsection{Union and Intersection}

The \textbf{union} of two sets \(A\) and \(B\) is the set of elements that are in \(A,\) in \(B,\) or in both \(A\) and \(B,\) but not any other elements. If the union of \(A\) and \(B\) is \(C,\) then we can write \(A\cup B=C.\)

The \textbf{intersection} of two sets \(A\) and \(B\) is the set of elements that are in both \(A\) and \(B.\) If an element fails to appear in at least one of the two sets, then it does not appear in the intersection. If the intersection of \(A\) and \(B\) is \(C,\) then we can write \(A\cap B=C.\)\\

\example Give the set equivalent to each of the following.
\begin{enumerate}[label=(\alph*)]
\item \(\{-1,0,6\}\cup\{2,3,6\}\)
\item \(\{x|\text{Positive factors of }30\}\cap\{x|\text{Multiples of }5\}\)
\item \(\{1,2,3,4\}\cap(\{0,2,4,6\}\cup\{-4,-1,2,5\}\)
\end{enumerate}
\solution
\begin{enumerate}[label=(\alph*)]
\item \(\{-1,0,2,3,6\}\)
\item \(\{1,2,3,5,6,10,15,30\}\cap\{\ldots,-5,0,5,10,\ldots\}=\{5,10,15\}\)
\item \(\{1,2,3,4\}\cap\{-4,-1,0,2,4,5,6\}=\{2,4\}\)
\end{enumerate}
\vspace{1em}

\subsection{Special Sets}

There are several sets that we will encounter very often throughout this course, which are described here. There are many other special sets of numbers, but they are not important to this class and are therefore not listed.

\begin{itemize}
\item \(\mathbb{C}\) represents the \textbf{complex numbers}. These are numbers that can be written in the form \(a+bi,\) where \(a\) and \(b\) are real constants and \(i=\sqrt{-1}.\) Even if \(a=0\) or \(b=0\) (or both), any number we will encounter in this course is complex.
\item \(\mathbb{R}\) represents the \textbf{real numbers}. These are complex numbers that have \(b=0.\) \(12\) and \(-\pi^3\) are real numbers, but \(5-3i\) is not a real number.
\item \(\mathbb{Z}\) represents the \textbf{integers}. These are numbers that, when expressed in decimal notation, have nothing after the decimal point (after being simplified fully). \(2\) is an integer, but \(\frac{7}{4}=1.75\) and \(\sqrt{3}=1.732\ldots\) are not integers.
\item \(\mathbb{N}\) represents the \textbf{natural numbers}. These are the positive integers \((\mathbb{Z}^+)\). Examples include \(7\) and \(12,802.\) Note that \(0\) is not a natural number; while \(0\) is non-negative, it is also not positive.
\end{itemize}

Some other sets you may encounter are \(\mathbb{Q}\) (\textbf{rationals}, which can be written in the form \(\frac{a}{b}\) for nonzero \(b\)), \(\mathbb{U}\) (\textbf{whole numbers}, which are non-negative integers), and \(\mathbb{I}\) (\textbf{imaginary numbers}, which are equal to \(bi\) for some real nonzero \(b\)).\\

\noindent \textit{Note: This text gives a cyclical definition of real and complex numbers because the formal definitions of the real and complex numbers are beyond the scope of this book.}

\subsection{Interval Notation}

\indent An \textbf{interval} is a subsection of the real line containing all real numbers strictly between the \textbf{endpoints} (and possibly the endpoints themselves). An interval is continuous; for example, the set of positive reals is continuous and is thus an interval, but the set of positive integers is non-continuous and is not an interval.

If the distance between the two endpoints of an interval is finite, then the interval is a \textbf{finite interval}. If the distance between the two endpoints is infinite, then the interval is an \textbf{infinite interval}.

Depending on if a finite interval contains its endpoints, an interval can be \textbf{open} (it contains neither of its endpoints), \textbf{half-open} (it contains exactly one of its enpoints), or \textbf{closed} (ot contains both of its enpoints). An infinite interval is considered closed if it contains its finite endpoints, and open otherwise. By convention, the set of reals is considered both open and closed. The following table describes how to denote these types of sets in \textbf{interval notation}.\\

\noindent \tablelabel 

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|}
\hline
\textbf{Notation} & \textbf{Function} & \textbf{Description} \\
\hline
\((a,b)\) & \(\{x|a<x<b\}\) & Open \\
\([a,b)\) & \(\{x|a\leq x<b\}\) & Half-open \\
\((a,b]\) & \(\{x|a<x\leq b\}\) & Half-open \\
\([a,b]\) & \(\{x|a\leq x\leq b\}\) & Closed \\
\((a,\infty)\) & \(\{x|x>a\}\) & Open \\
\([a,\infty)\) & \(\{x|x\geq a\}\) & Closed \\
\((-\infty,b)\) & \(\{x|x<b\}\) & Open \\
\((-\infty,b]\) & \(\{x|x\leq b\}\) & Closed \\
\((-\infty,\infty)\) & \(x\in\mathbb{R}\) & Both \\ \hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}
\example Solve the following inequalities and write your answer in interval notation.
\begin{enumerate}[label=(\alph*)]
\item \(4x+2<-x-3\)
\item \(\frac{3x+5}{8}+2\geq4\)
\item \(x^2-6x\leq16\)
\end{enumerate}
\solution
\begin{enumerate}[label=(\alph*)]
\item
\(
\begin{aligned}[t]
4x+2&<-x-3 && && \\
5x+2&<-3 && && {\scriptsize\color{blue}\text{Add }\scriptstyle{x}} \\
5x&<-5 && && {\scriptsize\color{blue}\text{Subtract }\scriptstyle{2}} \\
x&<-1 && &&  {\scriptsize\color{blue}\text{Divide by }\scriptstyle{5}} \\
x&\in(-\infty,-1) && \hspace{1em} &&  {\scriptsize\color{blue}\text{Interval notation}}
\end{aligned}
\)
\item
\(
\begin{aligned}[t]
\tfrac{3x+5}{8}+2&\geq4 && && \\
\tfrac{3x+5}{8}&\geq2 && && {\scriptsize\color{blue}\text{Subtract }\scriptstyle{2}} \\
3x+5&\geq16 && && {\scriptsize\color{blue}\text{Multiply by }\scriptstyle{8}} \\
3x&\geq11 && && {\scriptsize\color{blue}\text{Subtract }\scriptstyle{5}} \\
x&\geq\tfrac{11}{3} && && {\scriptsize\color{blue}\text{Divide by }\scriptstyle{3}} \\
x&\in[\tfrac{11}{3},\infty] && \hspace{1em} && {\scriptsize\color{blue}\text{Interval notation }}
\end{aligned}
\)
\item
\(
\begin{aligned}[t]
x^2-6x&\leq16 && && \\
x^2-6x-16&\leq0 && && {\scriptsize\color{blue}\text{Subtract }\scriptstyle{16}} \\
(x+2)(x-8)&\leq0 && && {\scriptsize\color{blue}\text{Factor}} \\
x&\in[-2,8] && \hspace{1em} && {\scriptsize\color{blue}\text{Interval notation}}
\end{aligned}
\)
\end{enumerate}

\section{Introduction to Functions}
\subsection{Properties of Functions}

A \textbf{relation} is an expression used to express a relationship between two variables. As one of the values of the variables changes, the value of the other variable should change accordingly. A function describes the relationship between two variables \(x\) and \(y\) by writing \(y\) in terms of \(x.\) We write \(y=f(x)\) and say ``\(y\) equals \(f\) of \(x\)" when we want to say that \(y\) depends on the value of \(x\) according to the function \(f.\)

Because we have made \(y\) change based on our different values of \(x,\) we call \(x\) the \textbf{independent variable} and \(y\) the \textbf{dependent variable}. You may have come across these terms in a science class.

A \textbf{function} is a relation between \(x\) and \(y\) expressed as \(y=f(x)\) that produces a unique value of \(y\) for a given value of \(x.\) This means that the function passes the \textbf{Vertical Line Test}. This test states that if a vertical line passes through the graph of a relation more than once, then the relation is not a function. For example, a circle centered at the origin with radius \(1\) is not a function because the vertical line \(x=0\) passes through it at two points - \((0,-1)\) and \((0,1).\)\\

\example Write a function to represent the following operations.
\begin{enumerate}
\item A number \(x\) multiplied by \(2\) and added to \(1\)
\item The area of a circle is \(\pi\) times the radius \((r)\) squared.
\item A number \(n\) multiplied by itself four times, then divided by
\(3\), then reduced by the number times \(2\)
\end{enumerate}
\solution
\begin{enumerate}
\item \(A(x)=2x+1\)
\item \(B(r)=\pi r^2\)
\item \(C(n)=\frac{n^4}{3}-2n\)
\end{enumerate}
\vspace{1em}

Note that we don't only have to use the letter \(f\) to represent functions. As you see, we can use other letters, and in other areas of mathematics, some of the symbols used to represent functions aren't even letters at all!

\subsection{Domain and Range}

Every function has a specific set of values of \(x\) that produce defined values of \(y.\) These values of \(x\) are referred to as the \textbf{domain} of the function, and the values of \(y\) they create are the \textbf{range}. It is much easier to find the domain of functions than it is to find the range. When written, domain and range are expressed in interval notation.

When we see a function, we should always assume it has the largest possible domain unless restrictions on the domain are explicitly given; for example, we should only assume \(f(x)=x^2\) has a domain of \([2,4)\) if we are told that \(f(x)=x^2,-2\leq x<4.\) This largest possible domain is called the \textbf{natural domain} of the function.

The domain of a function \(f(x)\) can be notated \(\mathfrak{D}(f).\) Similarly, the range of \(f\) is \(\mathfrak{R}.\)\\

\noindent There are several important rules to follow when taking the domain of a function.
\begin{itemize}
\item Never divide a number by \(0.\)
\item Never take the square root of a negative number.
\item Never take a logarithm of a non-positive number.
\end{itemize}
\noindent \textit{Note: If the word ``logarithm" in the third rule is unfamiliar to you, don't worry; it will be explained soon.}

\subsection{A Preview of Curve Sketching}

We can plug in specific values of \(x\) to find values of \(y.\) To do this, replace all of the \(x\)'s in the expression with the value of \(x\) you are using and simplify. For example, if \(f(x)=x^2+6\) and we wan to find \(f(4),\) we say \(f(4)=4^2+6=22.\) When written together, these \(x\) and \(y\) pairs are called \textbf{ordered pairs} and written in the form \((x,f(x)).\) A graph of a function is made up by plotting ordered pairs.

Two other ways to represent a function are numerically and graphically. We can compile a list of ordered pairs in a graph and then connect the dots we put on the graph. The closer we put the dots together, the more accurate our graph will be to the real thing. Let's try this out with the graph of \(y=x^2.\)\\

\noindent \tablelabel

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{|c|c|}
\hline
\(x\) & \(f(x)\) \\ \hline
\(-2\) & \(4\) \\
\(-1\) & \(1\) \\
\(0\) & \(0\) \\
\(0.25\) & \(0.0625\) \\
\(0.5\) & \(0.25\) \\
\(1\) & \(1\) \\
\(1.5\) & \(2.25\) \\
\(2\) & \(4\) \\ \hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}
Let's compare the graph created by plotting the above points to the actual graph of \(y=x^2.\)\\

\noindent \figurelabel
\begin{center}
%\begin{comment}
\begin{tikzpicture}

%Line segments
\begin{axis}[name=plot1,
grid=both,
axis lines=middle,
ticklabel style={fill=white,font=\scriptsize},
x=1cm,y=1cm,clip=false,
xmin=-2.5,xmax=2.5,xtick={-2,-1,1,2},
ymin=-1.5,ymax=4.5,ytick={-1,1,2,3,4},
xlabel=\(x\),ylabel=\(y\)]
\addplot[domain=-2:-1,<-,>=latex,samples=2] {-3*x-2};
\addplot[domain=-1:0,samples=2] {-1*x};
\addplot[domain=0:2,->,>=latex,samples=2] {x^2};
\end{axis}

%y=x^2
\begin{axis}[name=plot2,at={($(plot1.east)+(4em,0)$)},anchor=west,
grid=both,
axis lines=middle,
ticklabel style={fill=white,font=\scriptsize},
x=1cm,y=1cm,clip=false,
xmin=-2.5,xmax=2.5,xtick={-2,-1,1,2},
ymin=-1.5,ymax=4.5,ytick={-1,1,2,3,4},
xlabel=\(x\),ylabel=\(y\),
samples=200]
\addplot[domain=-2:2,<->,>=latex] {x^2};
\end{axis}

\end{tikzpicture}
%\end{comment}
\end{center}
Note how much more similar the right hand side of the first graph is to the second graph than the left hand side.

\section{Common functions}

We will now examine the graphs of many of the common functions we will use throughout this course. For simplicity, we will assume \(y=f(x)\) for this entire section.

\subsection{Power functions}

The simplest function is a \textbf{constant function}. This is a function of the form \(f(x)=b\) for some constant \(b.\) Another simple function is the \textbf{identity function} \(f(x)=x,\) which returns as an output the value that was inputted. Multiplying the identity function by a nonzero constant \(m\) makes \(y\) and \(x\) \textbf{directly proportional}; i.e. \(\frac{y}{x}=m.\) It is also worth noting that if \(xy=k,\) then \(x\) and \(y\) are \textbf{inversely proportional}. Here are the graphs of a constant function and \(y=mx\) for several values of \(m.\)\\

\noindent \figurelabel
\begin{center}
%\begin{comment}
\begin{tikzpicture}

\begin{axis}[grid=both,
axis lines=middle,
ticklabel style={fill=white,font=\scriptsize},
x=1cm,y=1cm,clip=false,
xmin=-3.5,xmax=3.5,xtick={-3,-2,-1,1,2,3},
ymin=-3.5,ymax=3.5,ytick={-3,-2,-1,1,2,3},
xlabel=\(x\),ylabel=\(y\),
samples=2,
legend style={at={(axis cs:4,2)},anchor=north west,font=\small},legend cell align=left,legend image post style=-]

\addplot[domain=-1.5:1.5,<->,>=latex,Green] {-2*x}; \addlegendentry{\text{ }\(y=-2x\)}
\addplot[domain=-3:3,<->,>=latex,Orange] {-1*x}; \addlegendentry{\text{ }\(y=-x\)}
\addplot[domain=-3:3,<->,>=latex,Red] {-1/2*x}; \addlegendentry{\text{ }\(y=-\frac{1}{2}x\)}
\addplot[domain=-3:3,<->,>=latex,Magenta] {1/2*x}; \addlegendentry{\text{ }\(y=\frac{1}{2}x\)}
\addplot[domain=-3:3,<->,>=latex,Purple] {x}; \addlegendentry{\text{ }\(y=x\)}
\addplot[domain=-1.5:1.5,<->,>=latex,Blue] {2*x}; \addlegendentry{\text{ }\(y=2x\)}
\addplot[domain=-3:3,<->,>=latex] {2.5}; \addlegendentry{\text{ }\(y=\frac{5}{2}\)}

\end{axis}

\end{tikzpicture}
%\end{comment}
\end{center}

When a constant and a scaled identity function are added together, we get the general equation of a \textbf{linear function}: \(y=mx+b.\) \(m\) is the slope of the function, and \(b\) is its \textbf{y-intercept} (where it crosses the \(y\)-axis). Note that the function crosses the \(x\)-axis at its \textbf{x-intercept} of \(-\frac{b}{m}.\) The graphs of two lines are shown.\\

\noindent \figurelabel

\begin{center}
%\begin{comment}
\begin{tikzpicture}

\begin{axis}[grid=both,
axis lines=middle,
ticklabel style={fill=white,font=\scriptsize},
x=1cm,y=1cm,clip=false,
xmin=-2.5,xmax=3.5,xtick={-2,-1,1,2,3},
ymin=-2.5,ymax=3.5,ytick={-2,-1,1,2,3},
xlabel=\(x\),ylabel=\(y\),
samples=2,
legend style={at={(axis cs:4,2)},anchor=north west,font=\small},legend cell align=left,legend image post style=-]

\addplot[domain=-2:2,<->,>=latex,Red] {5/4*x+1/2}; \addlegendentry{\text{ }\(y=\frac{5}{4}x+\frac{1}{2}\)}
\addplot[domain=-2:3,<->,>=latex,Blue] {-1/2*x+2}; \addlegendentry{\text{ }\(y=-\frac{1}{2}x+2\)}

\end{axis}

\end{tikzpicture}
%\end{comment}
\end{center}

The power of \(x\) in a function doesn't always have to be \(1.\) A function of the form \(f(x)=x^p\) for some constant \(p\) is known as a \textbf{power function}. We will now investigate the graphs of power functions for several important values of \(p.\)

{\large
\begin{itemize}
\item \hspace{0.5em}\(p\) is a positive integer
\end{itemize}
}

\noindent You have already seen the graph of \(y=x^1=x.\) Here are the graphs for \(p\in\{2,3,4,5\}.\)\\

\noindent \figurelabel

\begin{center}
%\begin{comment}
\begin{tikzpicture} 

