\vspace{-1em}Notice here how much steeper the graphs get as \(p\) grows larger. Also, the graphs of \(x^{2k}\) tend towards \(\infty\) as the \(x\) coordinate goes further away from the \(y\)-axis, while the graphs of \(x^{2k+1}\) tend towards \(\infty\) as the \(x\) coordinate moves further from the \(y\)-axis in a positive direction and towards \(-\infty\) as the \(x\) coordinate moves further from the \(y\)-axis in a negative direction. These are trends that will continue for integer \(p>5.\)\\

Different things happen, however, when \(p\) is a negative integer. Since \(x^{-k}=\frac{1}{x^k},\) the expression will not be defined when \(x=0.\) The line \(x=0\) is called an ``asymptote," but we will learn about these later on.

{\large
\begin{itemize}
\item \hspace{0.5em}\(p\) is a negative integer
\end{itemize}
}

\noindent Here are the graphs of \(x^{-p}\) for \(p\in\{1,2,3,4\}.\) Note that the functions are all undefined at \(x=0\) and \(|x^{p}|\) decreases as \(|x|\) increases.\\

\noindent \figurelabel

\begin{center}
%\begin{comment}
\begin{tikzpicture} 

%y=x^-1
\begin{axis}[name=plot1,
grid=both,
axis lines=middle,
x=0.4cm,y=0.4cm,clip=false,
xmin=-4,xmax=4,xtick={-3,-2,-1,1,2,3},xticklabels={\empty},
ymin=-4,ymax=4,ytick={-3,-2,-1,1,2,3},yticklabels={\empty},
extra x tick style={ticklabel style={fill=white,font=\scriptsize},xticklabel={1}},extra x ticks={1},
extra y tick style={ticklabel style={fill=white,font=\scriptsize},yticklabel={1}},extra y ticks={1},
xlabel=\(x\),ylabel=\(y\),
samples=188]
\addplot[domain=-4:-0.250,<->,>=latex] {x^-1};
\addplot[domain=0.250:4,<->,>=latex] {x^-1};
\node[label={270:{\(y=x^{-1}\)}},inner sep=4pt] at (axis cs:0,-4) {};
\end{axis}

%y=x^-2
\begin{axis}[name=plot2,at={($(plot1.east)+(2em,0)$)},anchor=west,
grid=both,
axis lines=middle,
x=0.4cm,y=0.4cm,clip=false,
