\end{tikzpicture}
%\end{comment}
\end{center}

You may notice how the shape of these graphs depends on if \(p\) is even or odd. This makes sense, as all of these functions are \(1\) divided by the \(x^p\) graphs we saw earlier. \(1\) is a positive number. Thus, \(1\) divided by a negative number is a negative number, and \(1\) divided by a positive number is also positive. Looking back at the \(x^p\) graphs, we see that only functions of the form \(y=x^{2k+1}\) have \(y\)-coordinates in the negative numbers. This means that \(y=\frac{1}{x^{2k+1}}\) also has \(y\)-coordinates in the negative numbers. Additionally, as \(p\) increases, the curvature of the graph of \(y=x^{-p}\) becomes more pronounced. 

{\large
\begin{itemize}
\item \hspace{0.5em}\(p\) is a positive fraction
\end{itemize}
}

When considering \(x^p\) with positive non-integer \(p,\) we have to ask the following question: is \(p\) greater or less than \(1?\)

\begin{itemize}
\item \hspace{0.5em}\(p>1\)
\end{itemize}

The graph will have a very similar shape to that of graphs of other \(y=x^p\) with integer \(p\geq2,\) but this is only guaranteed in the first quadrant. The domain may not allow for negative values of \(x.\) Let's write \(x^p=x^\frac{a}{b}\) for positive integer \(a\) and \(b\) that share no factors other than \(1\) (they are \textbf{coprime}).

Remember that \(x^\frac{a}{b}\) can be written as \(\sqrt[b]{x^a}\). If \(b\) is even, then \(x^a\) must be positive, or the expression would not be defined. Thus, if \(b\) is even, then the domain of \(y=x^\frac{a}{b}\) is \([0,\infty).\) However, if \(b\) is odd, then the domain of \(x^\frac{a}{b}\) is \(\mathbb{R}.\)\\

\noindent Here are the graphs of two power functions with non-integer \(p>1.\)\\

\noindent \figurelabel

\begin{center}
%\begin{comment}
\begin{tikzpicture} 

%y=x^(3/2)
\begin{axis}[name=plot1,
grid=both,
axis lines=middle,
ticklabel style={fill=white,font=\scriptsize},
x=0.8cm,y=0.8cm,clip=false,
xmin=-2,xmax=2,xtick={-1,1},
ymin=-1,ymax=3,ytick={1,2},
xlabel=\(x\),ylabel=\(y\),
samples=100]
\addplot[domain=0:2,->,>=latex] {x^(3/2)};
\node[label={270:{\(y=x^\frac{3}{2}\)}},inner sep=4pt] at (axis cs:0,-1) {};
\end{axis}

%y=x^(7/3)
\begin{axis}[name=plot1,at={($(plot1.east)+(4em,0)$)},anchor=west,
grid=both,
axis lines=middle,
ticklabel style={fill=white,font=\scriptsize},
x=0.8cm,y=0.8cm,clip=false,
xmin=-2,xmax=2,xtick={-1,1},
ymin=-2,ymax=2,ytick={-1,1},
xlabel=\(x\),ylabel=\(y\),
samples=135]
\addplot[domain=-1.346:1.346,<->,>=latex] {x/abs(x)*(abs(x))^(7/3)};
\node[label={270:{\(y=x^\frac{7}{3}\)}},inner sep=4pt] at (axis cs:0,-2) {};
\end{axis}

\end{tikzpicture}
%\end{comment}
\end{center}

\begin{itemize}
\item \hspace{0.5em}\(p<1\)
\end{itemize}

Like we did with the case where \(p>1,\) let's write \(x^p=x^\frac{a}{b}.\) We have the same domain issue: if \(b\) is even, then the domain of \(x^\frac{a}{b}\) is \([0,\infty)\), and if \(b\) is odd, then the domain of \(x^\frac{a}{b}\) is \(\mathbb{R}.\) The difference between the case where \(p<1\) and the case where \(p>1\) is that the graphs of the functions with \(p<1\) look like the graphs of \(p<1\) turned \(90^\circ\) to the right and then flipped over the \(x\)-axis. This is equivalent to a rotation over the line \(y=x.\) However, it is not a rotation of the \textit{whole} function over \(y=x.\) Notice that the graph of \(y=\sqrt{x}\) only lies in the first quadrant, not the fourth as well. This is because \(\sqrt{x}\) takes the principal root of \(x.\) While \(4^2=(-4)^2=16,\) \(4\) is the principal square root of \(16.\)

It is important to know that \(y=\sqrt{x}\) is known as the \textbf{square root function} and that \(y=\sqrt[3]{x}\) is known as the \textbf{cube root function}. Here are their graphs.\\

\noindent \figurelabel

\begin{center}
