%\end{comment}
\end{center}

\subsection{Polynomials}

A \textbf{polynomial} is a summation of power functions multiplied by constants under the condition that the power to which \(x\) is raised in each term is a non-negative integer. For example, \(f(x)=x^2+6x+10\) is a polynomial, but \(g(x)=2x^2+9-\frac{3}{x^4}\) and \(h(x)=9\pi\sqrt{x}\) are not. The following gives the general form for a polynomial.
\[f(x)=a_nx^n+a_{n-1}x^{n-1}+\ldots+a_1x+a_0\]
\hspace{2em} The numbers \(\{a_0,a_1,\ldots,a_n\}\) are referred to as \textbf{coefficients}. These coefficients can be equal to any real number, including \(0.\) A polynomial does not necessarily have a nonzero term for every \(x^k\) for \(k\) an integer in \([0,n].\) The exponent of the highest power of \(x\) that has a nonzero coefficient (in our general form, \(n\)) is known as the \textbf{degree} of the polynomial. For example, the degree of \(f(x)=0x^4+2x^3-x^2+6\) is \(3.\)

The degree of a constant function \(y=c\) is \(0,\) except for \(y=0,\) which has an undefined degree. The degree of a linear function \(y=mx+b\) with \(m\neq0\) is \(1.\) When the degree of a polynomial is \(2,\) the polynomial is known as a \textbf{quadratic function} and is written in the form \(y=ax^2+bx+c.\) When the degree is \(3,\) the polynomial is called a \textbf{cubic function} and is written in the form \(y=ax^3+bx^2+cx+d.\) Here are two graphs of polynomials.\\

\noindent \figurelabel

\begin{center}
%\begin{comment}
\begin{tikzpicture} 

%y=-x^2+x+1
\begin{axis}[name=plot1,
grid=both,
axis lines=middle,
ticklabel style={fill=white,font=\scriptsize},
x=0.6cm,y=0.6cm,clip=false,
xmin=-2,xmax=4,xtick={2},
ymin=-6,ymax=2,ytick={-4,-2},
xlabel=\(x\),ylabel=\(y\),
samples=260]
\addplot[domain=-2:3.192,<->,>=latex] {-1*x^2+x+1};
\node[label={270:{\(y=-x^2+x+1\)}},inner sep=4pt] at (axis cs:1,-6) {};
\end{axis}

%y=x^3-3x^2+2x-4
\begin{axis}[name=plot2,at={($(plot1.east)+(4em,0)$)},anchor=west,
grid=both,
