\end{axis}

\end{tikzpicture}
%\end{comment}
\end{center}

The domain of all polynomials is \(\mathbb{R}.\)

\subsection{Rational Functions}

A \textbf{rational function} is the division of one polynomial by another. We can say \(f(x)=\frac{a(x)}{b(x)}.\) The domain of a rational function is the set of all real \(x\) except those such that \(b(x)=0.\) The graphs of rational functions often have asymptotes, which will be discussed in the next chapter. Here are the graphs of several rational functions. Note that the red dotted lines are asymptotes, which are not part of the actual function.\\

\noindent \figurelabel

