\end{center}

The graph above on the left is a semicircle with radius \(3.\) \(y=\sqrt{r^2-x^2}\) is the equation of a semicircle with radius \(r.\) It can be derived by taking the principle root when solving for \(y\) in the standard equation of a circle: \(x^2+y^2=r^2.\) This will become important when we begin to cover the areas of regions.

\subsection{Trigonometric Functions (Introduction)}

There are six major \textbf{trigonometric functions}: \textbf{sine}, \textbf{cosine}, \textbf{tangent}, \textbf{cotangent}, \textbf{secant}, and \textbf{cosecant}. Here are the graphs of the sine and cosine functions.\\

\noindent \figurelabel

%Add graph from original document

The six trigonometric functions can be represented as ratios of a right triangle's side lengths.  Let \(O\) equal the length of the side opposite \(\theta,\) let \(A\) equal the length of the side adjacent to \(\theta,\) and let \(H\) equal the length of the hypotenuse. We have the following relations.\\

\noindent \figurelabel

%Add graph from original document

\begin{alignat*}{5}
\sin\theta=\frac{O}{H}&\hspace{2em}&&\tan\theta=\frac{O}{A}&&\hspace{2em}\sec\theta=\frac{A}{H}\\
\cos\theta=\frac{A}{H}&\hspace{2em}&&\cot\theta=\frac{A}{O}&&\hspace{2em}\csc\theta=\frac{O}{H}
\end{alignat*}

We will learn more about trigonometric functions in section \(1.7.\)

\subsection{Exponential Functions (Introduction)}

An \textbf{exponential function} is a function of the form \(f(x)=a^x,\) where \(a\) is some positive constant not equal to \(1\) (the function \(f(x)=1^x\) is the same as the constant function \(g(x)=1\)).

There are certain properties that all exponential functions have. The domain of exponential functions is \(\mathbb{R}.\) Additionally, the \(y\)-coordinates of exponential functions can get arbitrarily close to \(0\) but not actually reach it. Reaching \(\infty\) is possible by taking sufficiently large \(x\) in either the positive or negative direction. This means the range of all exponential functions is \((0,\infty).\) Also, since \(a^0=1\Forall a,\) all exponential functions pass through the point \((0,1).\) In the graphs below, you will notice that \(a^x\) is the reflection of \(\left(\frac{1}{a}\right)^x\) over the \(y\)-axis.\\

\noindent \textit{Note: The following graphs are not to scale.}\\

\noindent \figurelabel

\begin{center}
%\begin{comment}
\begin{tikzpicture}

%y=2^x, y=e^x, y=10^x
\begin{axis}[name=plot1,
grid=both,
axis lines=middle,
ticklabel style={fill=white,font=\scriptsize},
x=1.6cm,y=0.4cm,clip=false,
xmin=-1.5,xmax=1.5,xtick={-1,-0.5,0.5,1},
ymin=-2,ymax=12,ytick={2,4,6,8,10},
xlabel=\(x\),ylabel=\(y\)]
\addplot[Blue,domain=-1.5:1.5,<->,>=latex,samples=150] {2^x};
\addplot[Green,domain=-1.5:1.5,<->,>=latex,samples=150] {e^x};
