\noindent\makebox[\linewidth]{\rule{\textwidth}{0.5pt}}

%Exercises

\noindent{\color{Gray}{\makebox[\linewidth]{\rule{\textwidth}{2pt}}}}

\section{Shifting and Scaling Functions}

So far we have only dealt with functions of the form \(y=f(x).\) In this section, we will  observe what happens to the graph of the function \(y=af(bx)+c.\)

\subsection{Function Operations}

Like numbers, functions can also be added, subtracted, multiplied, and divided (as long as the denominator isn't \(0.\)) These operations can produce a new function out of the two (or more) predecessor functions. Let us establish correct notation.
\begin{align*}
f(x)+g(x)&=(f+g)(x)\\
f(x)-g(x)&=(f-g)(x)\\
f(x)g(x)&=(fg)(x)\\
\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}&=\left(\frac{f}{g}\right)(x)
\end{align*}

The domains of these combined functions are the intersections of the domains of the functions that make them up. \(\mathfrak{D}(f+g)=\mathfrak{D}(f-g)=\mathfrak{D}(fg)=\mathfrak{D}(f)\cap\mathfrak{D}(g).\) We also have \(\mathfrak{D}\left(\frac{f}{g}\right)=\mathfrak{D}(f)\cap\mathfrak{D}(g)|g(x)\neq0.\)

As a special case of the multiplication rule, functions can also be multiplied by constants. The function \(y=cf(x)\) has the same domain of \(f(x).\)\\

\example If \(f(x)=\sqrt{x^2-1}\) and \(g(x)=\frac{1}{x+4},\) find the following functions and their respective domains.

\begin{enumerate}[label=(\alph*)]
\item \((f+g)(x)\)
\item \((f-g)(x)\)
\item \((g-f)(x)\)
\item \((fg)(x)\)
\item \(\left(\frac{f}{g}\right)(x)\)
\item \(\left(\frac{g}{f}\right)(x)\)
\end{enumerate}
\solution\\

We must first find the domains of \(f(x)\) and \(g(x).\) For the domain of \(f(x),\) we have \(x\in\mathfrak{D}(\sqrt{x^2-1}),\) so \(x^2-1\geq0.\) This simplifies to \(x^2\geq1,\) so \(x\in(-\infty,-1]\cup[1,\infty).\) For the domain of \(g(x),\) we have \(x\in\mathfrak{D}\left(\frac{1}{x+4}\right),\) so \(x+4\neq0.\) This simplifies to \(x\in(-\infty,-4)\cup(-4,\infty).\)
\begin{enumerate}[label=(\alph*)]
\item
\(f(x)+g(x)=\sqrt{x^2-1}+\frac{1}{x+4}.\) The domain of this function is \(\mathfrak{D}(f)\cap\mathfrak{D}(g)=(-\infty,-4)\cup(-4,-1]\cup[1,\infty).\)
\item \(f(x)-g(x)=\sqrt{x^2-1}-\frac{1}{x+4}.\) The domain of this function is \(\mathfrak{D}(f)\cap\mathfrak{D}(g)=(-\infty,-4)\cup(-4,-1]\cup[1,\infty).\)
\item \(g(x)-f(x)=\frac{1}{x+4}-\sqrt{x^2-1}.\) The domain of this function is \(\mathfrak{D}(f)\cap\mathfrak{D}(g)=(-\infty,-4)\cup(-4,-1]\cup[1,\infty).\)
\item \(f(x)g(x)=\frac{\sqrt{x^2-1}}{x+4}.\) The domain of this function is \(\mathfrak{D}(f)\cap\mathfrak{D}(g)=(-\infty,-4)\cup(-4,-1]\cup[1,\infty).\)
\item \(\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}=(x+4)\sqrt{x^2-1}.\) The domain of this function is \(\mathfrak{D}(f)\cap\mathfrak{D}(g)|g(x)\neq0.\) We find that \(g(x)\) does not equal \(0\) for any value of \(x,\) so the domain of this function is \((-\infty,-4)\cup(-4,-1]\cup[1,\infty).\)
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Composite Functions}

Let \(f(x)\) and \(g(x)\) be arbitrary functions. We define the \textbf{composite function} to be \(f(g(x)),\) also written as \((f\circ g)(x).\) This new function takes a number \(x,\) returns \(g(x),\) then uses the value of \(g(x)\) as the input to \(f(x).\) See the below figure.

%Figure from original

The domain of \(f(g(x))\) consists of all of the numbers in the domain of \(g(x)\) such that the value of \(g(x)\) is in the domain of \(f(x).\) An important thing to know is that \(f(g(x))\) is not necessarily equal to \(g(f(x)).\)\\

\example Let \(f(x)=\sqrt{x-3}\) and let \(g(x)=2x^2-5.\) Find the functions that represent each of the following and give their domains.

\begin{enumerate}[label=(\alph*)]
\item \((f\circ g)(x)\)
\item \((g\circ f)(x)\)
\item \((f\circ f)(x)\)
\item \((g\circ g)(x)\)
\end{enumerate}
\solution\\

\begin{enumerate}[label=(\alph*)]
\item \((f\circ g)(x)=f(g(x))=f(2x^2-5)=\sqrt{(2x^2-5)-3}=\sqrt{2x^2-8}\)\\
\(\mathfrak{D}=(-\infty,-2]\cup[2,\infty)\)
\item \((g\circ f)(x)=g(f(x))=2(g(x))^2=2(\sqrt{x-3})^2-5=2(x-3)-5=2x-11\)\\
\(\mathfrak{D}=[3,\infty)\)
\item \((f\circ f)(x)=f(f(x))=f(\sqrt{x-3})=\sqrt{\sqrt{x-3}-3}\)\\
\(\mathfrak{D}=[12,\infty)\)
\item \((g\circ g)(x)=g(g(x))=g(2x^2-5)=2(2x^2-5)^2-5=2(4x^2-20x+25)-5=8x^2-40x+45\)\\
\(\mathfrak{D}=(-\infty,\infty)\)
\end{enumerate}

Note that the domain of the function \(f(x)=2x-11\) is \((-\infty,\infty),\) but when it is formed by the composite function \(g\circ f\) in the previous example, the domain of \(f\) is \([3,\infty),\) so the domain is restricted.

\subsection{Even and Odd Functions}

Certain functions \(f(x)\) have \textbf{symmetry} properties that can be found by examining the composite function produced by taking \(f(-x).\) A function \(y=f(x)\) is referred to as an \textbf{even function} if \(f(-x)=f(x)\Forall x,\) and an \textbf{odd function} if \(f(-x)=-f(x)\Forall x.\) We will now examine the properties of even and odd functions.

Because \(f(-x)=f(x),\) an even function is symmetric about the \(y\)-axis. This means that if you flip the function over the \(y\)-axis, then you will get the exact same function. Note that if the point \((a,b)\) is on the graph of an even function, then so is the point \((-a,b).\)

Because \(f(-x)=-f(x),\) an odd function is symmetric about the origin. This means that if you rotate the function \(180^\circ\) around the point \((0,0),\) then you will get the exact same function. Note that if the point \((a,b)\) is on the graph of an odd function, then so is the point \((-a,-b).\) If \(x=0\) is in the domain of an odd function, then the function passes through the origin.\\

\example Determine if the following functions are even, odd, or neither.

\begin{enumerate}[label=(\alph*)]
\item \(f(x)=x^3+4x\)
\item \(f(x)=3x^4\cos x+5x^3\)
\item \(f(x)=\frac{-2x^3\sin x}{x^2+1}\)
\item \(f(x)=0\)
\end{enumerate}
\solution

\begin{enumerate}[label=(\alph*)]
\item \(f(-x)=(-x)^3+4(-x)=-x^3-4x=-f(x)\Rightarrow\) Odd
\item \(f(-x)=3(-x)^4\cos(-x)+5(-x)^3=3x^4\cos x-5x^3\Rightarrow\) Neither
\item \(f(-x)=\frac{-2(-x)^3\sin(-x)}{(-x)^2+1}=\frac{2x^3\times-\sin x}{x^2+1}=\frac{-2x^3\sin x}{x^2+1}=f(x)\Rightarrow\) Even
\item \(f(-x)=0=\pm f(x)\Rightarrow\) Both odd and even
\end{enumerate}

\section{Shifting and Scaling Functions}

We have already seen that we can add and multiply functions together to produce new functions, as well as combine functions together to produce composite. In this section, we will examine how this affects the properties of a function.

\subsection{Shifting Functions}

We can shift a function \(f(x)\) up or down by adding a nonzero constant. We can write the shift as \(f(x)+k.\) If \(k>0,\) then the new function lies above the old one; we are shifting the function up. If \(k<0,\) then the new function lies below the old one; we are shifting the function down. In both cases, we shift the function \(|k|\) units.

Similarly, we can also shift functions left or right by using a composite function. We can write the shift as \(f(x+k).\) If \(k>0,\) then the new function lies to the left of the old one. If \(k<0,\) then the new function lies to the right of the old one. In both cases, we shift the function \(|k|\) units.

These graphs show several shifts of the graph of \(y=x^2.\)\\

\noindent \figurelabel

\begin{center}
%\begin{comment}
\begin{tikzpicture}

%y=x^2, y=x^2+3, y=x^2-1
\begin{axis}[name=plot1,
grid=both,
axis lines=middle,
ticklabel style={fill=white,font=\scriptsize},
x=0.5cm,y=0.5cm,clip=false,
xmin=-3,xmax=3,xtick={-2,2},
ymin=-2,ymax=6,ytick={2,4},
xlabel=\(x\),ylabel=\(y\)]
\addplot[Blue,domain=-2.449:2.449,<->,>=latex,samples=245] {x^2};
\addplot[Green,domain=-1.732:1.732,<->,>=latex,samples=173] {x^2+3};
