\subsection{Scaling Functions}

In addition to shifting functions, we are also able to stretch or compress them horizontally and vertically. We can stretch a function vertically by multiplying the function by a positive constant. The function \(y=kf(x)\) is the function \(y=f(x)\) stretched vertically by a factor of \(k.\) By convention, if \(k<1,\) then we write \(y=\frac{1}{k}f(x)\) and say we are compressing \(f(x)\) by a factor of \(k.\) We can multiply the function by \(-1\) to reflect the function over the \(x\)-axis.

We can stretch or compress a function horizontally by combining a function \(y=f(x)\) and a linear function passing through the origin (\(y=kx\)). The function \(y=f(kx)\) is the function \(y=f(x)\) compressed horizontally by a factor of \(k.\) By convention, if \(K<1,\) then we write \(y=f\left(\frac{x}{k}\right)\) and say we are stretching \(f(x)\) by a factor of \(k.\) We can multiply the function by \(-1\) to reflect the function over the \(y\)-axis.

These graphs show the scaling of the graph of \(y=\sqrt{x}.\)\\

\noindent \figurelabel

\begin{center}
