\end{axis}

\end{tikzpicture}
%\end{comment}
\end{center}

\example Let \(f(x)=4x^2-9x+3.\) Find the new formula for \(f(x)\) if you perform the following movements.
\begin{enumerate}[label=(\alph*)]
\item Reflect \(f(x)\) about the \(x\)-axis, then stretch horizontally by a factor of \(3\).
\item Shift \(f(x)\) by \(2\) to the left and \(6\) down.
\item Reflect \(f(x)\) about the \(y\)-axis, then \(1\) up.
\end{enumerate}
\solution

\begin{enumerate}[label=(\alph*)]
\item
\(
\begin{aligned}[t]
-f\left(\frac{x}{3}\right)&=-\left(4\left(\frac{x}{3}\right)^2-9\left(\frac{x}{3}\right)+3\right)\\
&=-\left(\frac{4}{9}x^2-3x+3\right)\\
&=-\frac{4}{9}x^2+3x-3
\end{aligned}
\)
\item
\(
\begin{aligned}[t]
f(x+2)-5&=(4(x+2)^2-9(x+2)+3)-6\\
&=(4(x^2+4x+4)-(9x+18)+3)-6\\
&=(4x^2+7x+1)-6\\
&=4x^2+7x-5
\end{aligned}
\)
\item
\(
\begin{aligned}[t]
f(-x)+1&=(4(-x)^2-9(-x)+3)+1\\
&=(4x^2+9x+3)+1\\
&=4x^2+9x+4
\end{aligned}
\)
\end{enumerate}

%Exercises

\section{Piecewise Functions}

We are not able to express all functions using one simple \(y=f(x)\) formula. Suppose we were modeling the altitude of a plane before and after takeoff. Before takeoff, the plane would be at a constant altitude of \(0.\) After takeoff, we can say the the plane behaves according to some function. For simplicity, let's say the plane rises at a rate of \(1600\) feet per minute until reaching \(32,000\) feet, at which point it stops rising and remains at constant altitude. There's no function that can represent that graph; this is where piecewise functions come in. A \textbf{piecewise function} is a function that assigns a different operation to a given value of \(x\) in its domain, depending on which range that value of \(x\) falls in.

\subsection{Notation}

Consider a function that increases a number \(x\) by \(3\) if \(x\) is negative and multiplies \(x\) by \(2\) if \(x\) is non-negative. This is a combination of two linear functions and cannot be expressed in terms of one single linear function. We can express this piecewise function like this:

\[
f(x)=
\begin{cases}
x+2 & \text{if }x<0\\
3x & \text{if }x\geq0
\end{cases}
\]

\subsection{Common Piecewise Functions}

One of the simplest piecewise functions is the \textbf{signum} function (which is also denoted \(\sgn(x)\)). This function tells if the inputted number is positive, negative, or neither. If the input is positive, the signum function returns a value of \(1.\) If the input is negative, the function returns an input of \(-1.\) By convention, \(\sgn(0)=0.\) We can write this in piecewise notation like this.

\[
\sgn(x)=
\begin{cases}
1 & \text{if }x>0\\
0 & \text{if }x=0\\
-1 & \text{if }x<0
\end{cases}
\]

\noindent \figurelabel

\begin{center}
%\begin{comment}
\begin{tikzpicture}

%y=sgn(x)
\begin{axis}[grid=both,
axis lines=middle,
ticklabel style={fill=white,font=\scriptsize},
x=1cm,y=1cm,clip=false,
xmin=-3,xmax=3,xtick={-2,-1,1,2},
ymin=-2,ymax=2,ytick={-1,1},
xlabel=\(x\),ylabel=\(y\),
samples=2]
\addplot[domain=-3:0,<-,>=latex] {-1};
\addplot[domain=0:3,->,>=latex] {1};
\addplot[soldot] coordinates{(0,0)};
\addplot[holdot] coordinates{(0,-1)(0,1)};
\node[label={270:{\(y=\sgn(x)\)}},inner sep=4pt] at (axis cs:0,-2) {};
\end{axis}

\end{tikzpicture}
%\end{comment}
\end{center}

You are likely familiar with the \textbf{absolute value function}, which measures the distance between a point on the number line and zero. You have likely used the notation \(f(x)=|x|.\) Remember that when \(x\) is positive, then \(|x|=x,\) and that when \(x\) is negative, \(|x|=-x.\) Lastly, \(|0|=0.\) We can now use any of the following notations (though the middle notation is preferred).
\[
f(x)=
\begin{cases}
x & \text{if }x>0\\
0 & \text{if }x=0\\
-x & \text{if }x<0
\end{cases}
\hspace{2em}
=
\begin{cases}
x & \text{if }x\geq0\\
-x & \text{if }x<0
\end{cases}
\hspace{2em}
=
\begin{cases}
x & \text{if }x>0\\
-x & \text{if }x\leq0
\end{cases}
\]

It should be noted that \(|x|=x\sgn(x).\)\\

\noindent \figurelabel

\begin{center}
%\begin{comment}
\begin{tikzpicture}

%y=sgn(x)
\begin{axis}[grid=both,
axis lines=middle,
ticklabel style={fill=white,font=\scriptsize},
x=1cm,y=1cm,clip=false,
xmin=-3,xmax=3,xtick={-2,-1,1,2},
ymin=-1,ymax=3,ytick={1,2},
xlabel=\(x\),ylabel=\(y\),
samples=2]
\addplot[domain=-3:0,<-,>=latex] {-1*x};
\addplot[domain=0:3,->,>=latex] {x};
\node[label={270:{\(y=|x|\)}},inner sep=4pt] at (axis cs:0,-1) {};
\end{axis}

\end{tikzpicture}
%\end{comment}
\end{center}

An important function in physics is known as the \textbf{Heaviside function}, \(H(t)\). This function describes the state of an electric circuit once the circuit is closed at \(t=0.\) Before \(t=0,\) the Heaviside function returns a value of \(0\) (meaning the circuit is open), and after \(t=0,\) the Heaviside function returns a value of \(1.\) By convention, \(H(0)\) is taken to be equal to \(\frac{1}{2}\).\\

\example Write a piecewise function to represent the Heaviside function, and express the Heaviside function in terms of the signum function.\\

\solution 

\noindent From the above definition, we can write the following.
\[
H(x)=
\begin{cases}
1 & \text{if }x>0\\
\frac{1}{2} & \text{if }x=0\\
0 & \text{if }x<0
\end{cases}
\]
We see that \(H(x)=\frac{\sgn(x)+1}{2}.\)\\

\section{Trigonometric Functions}

\subsection{Angles}

An \textbf{angle} is created when two rays share a common endpoint; the angle is a measure of the space between the rays. Angles are usually measured in degrees or radians. For this course, all angles are assumed to be in radians unless otherwise specified.

The \textbf{radian} is defined as the ratio of the length of an arc of a circle to the radius of the circle and is used to describe how wide an angle is.

%diagram

In the above diagram, we say that \(\frac{s}{r}=\theta\) radians.

The \textbf{unit circle} is the circle with radius \(1\) centered at the origin. Since \(r=1,\) the length of the arc produced when the rays of an angle centered at the origin intersect the unit circle is equal to the angle's measure in radians. We know that in a full rotation of a circle, there are \(360^\circ.\) The circumference of a circle with radius \(r\) is \(2\pi r,\) so the circumference of the unit circle is \(2\pi.\) This means \(360^\circ=2\pi\) radians, or \(180^\circ=\pi\) radians.

We can now make the following conversions.
\[1\text{ radian}=\frac{180}{\pi}^\circ\approx57.30^\circ\hspace{3em}1^\circ=\frac{\pi}{180}\approx0.0175\text{ radians}\]

\noindent \textit{Note: Typically, when an angle is expressed in radians, there is no unit; the unit of ``radians" is implied.}

The following angle measure conversions are extremely important to know. It is recommended that the student memorize these conversions and not have to derive the radian measure from the degree measure when solving a problem.\\

\noindent \tablelabel

\begin{center}
\renewcommand*{\arraystretch}{1.3}
\begin{tabular}{|>{\xstrut}l|c|c|c|c|c|c|c|c|c}
\hline
Degrees & \(0\) & \(30\) & \(45\) & \(60\) & \(90\) & \(120\) & \(135\) & \(150\) & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{\(180\)} \\ \hline
Radians & \(0\)  & \(\frac{\pi}{6}\) & \(\frac{\pi}{4}\) & \(\frac{\pi}{3}\) & \(\frac{\pi}{2}\) & \(\frac{2\pi}{3}\) & \(\frac{3\pi}{4}\) & \(\frac{5\pi}{6}\) & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{\(\pi\)} \\ \hline\hline
Degrees & \(210\) & \(225\) & \(240\) & \(270\) & \(300\) & \(315\) & \(330\) & \(360\) & \\ \cline{1-9}
Radians & \(\frac{7\pi}{6}\) & \(\frac{5\pi}{4}\) & \(\frac{4\pi}{3}\) & \(\frac{3\pi}{2}\) & \(\frac{5\pi}{3}\) & \(\frac{7\pi}{4}\) & \(\frac{11\pi}{6}\) & \(2\pi\) & \\ \cline{1-9}
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

An angle is said to be in \textbf{standard position} if one of the rays that makes it up is the positive \(x\)-axis (this ray is called the \textbf{initial ray}; the other ray that determines the angle is called the \textbf{terminal ray}). In this course, we will always assume that an angle is in standard position unless otherwise specified.

The measure of an angle does not necessarily have to be between \(0\) and \(2\pi.\) We can rotate an angle as many times as much as we want, as long as the terminal ray is still in the same place. If two angles have different measures but have common terminal rays, then the angles are said to be \textbf{coterminal}. The below graph shows that \(\frac{5\pi}{3},\) \(-\frac{\pi}{3},\) and \(\frac{17\pi}{3}\) are all coterminal.\\

\noindent \figurelabel

%Graph

\subsection{The Six Basic Functions}

Many students may have learned the basic definitions of the trigonometric functions as the ratios of sides on a right triangle. However, this text will demonstrate the trigonometric functions with the \textbf{unit circle}, a circle with radius \(1\) centered at the origin.\\

\noindent \figurelabel

%Graph

We have the following relations with the figure above.
\begin{alignat*}{3}
\textbf{Sine: }\sin\theta=\frac{y}{r}\hspace{3em}\textbf{Cosine: }&\cos\theta=\frac{x}{r}\hspace{3em}\textbf{Tangent: }&&\tan\theta=\frac{y}{x}\\
\textbf{Cosecant: }\csc\theta=\frac{r}{y}\hspace{3em}\textbf{Secant: }&\sec\theta=\frac{r}{x}\hspace{3em}\textbf{Cotangent: }&&\cot\theta=\frac{x}{y}
\end{alignat*}

From these, we also have the following.

\begin{align*}
\tan\theta=\frac{\sin\theta}{\cos\theta}\hspace{3em}&\cot\theta=\frac{\cos\theta}{\sin\theta}=\frac{1}{\tan\theta}\\
\sec\theta=\frac{1}{\cos\theta}\hspace{3em}&\csc\theta=\frac{1}{\sin\theta}
\end{align*}

These definitions, unlike the ones based on right triangles, work when the angle isn't acute.

\subsection{ASTC}

Let's take a moment to think about the geometric definitions of sine and cosine. As we saw in Figure \(1.19,\) the point where the terminal ray of an angle intersects the unit circle is the point \((\cos\theta,\sin\theta).\) Since \(f(-x)\) is the reflection of \(f(x)\) over the \(y\)-axis, we see that \(\sin(-x)=-\sin x\) and \(\cos(-x)=\cos x.\) From these, we can derive the following.
\begin{align*}
\tan(-\theta)=-\tan\theta\hspace{3em}&\cot(-\theta)=-\cot\theta\\
\cot(-\theta)=-\cot\theta\hspace{3em}&\csc(-\theta)=-\csc\theta
\end{align*}
This shows that cosine and secant are even functions, while sine, cosecant, tangent, and cotangent are odd functions.

From this, we can make the following diagram to know what functions are positive in what quadrant.\\

\noindent \figurelabel
\begin{center}
%\begin{comment}
\begin{tikzpicture}

\begin{axis}[axis lines=middle,
ticklabel style={none},
x=4cm,y=4cm,clip=false,
xmin=-1,xmax=1,xtick=\empty,
ymin=-1,ymax=1,ytick=\empty,
xlabel=\(x\),ylabel=\(y\)]

\node[label={0:{\Huge A}},inner sep=0pt] at (axis cs:0.4,0.5) {};
\node[label={180:{\Huge S}},inner sep=0pt] at (axis cs:-0.4,0.5) {};
\node[label={180:{\Huge T}},inner sep=0pt] at (axis cs:-0.4,-0.5) {};
\node[label={0:{\Huge C}},inner sep=0pt] at (axis cs:0.4,-0.5) {};

\end{axis}

\end{tikzpicture}
%\end{comment}
\end{center}

The A stands for ``All" because all six trigonometric functions are positive in the first quadrant. S stands for ``sine," because sine (and cosecant) are positive in the second quadrant. T stands for ``tangent," since tangent and cotangent are positive in the third quadrant. Lastly, C stands for ``cosine," since it and secant are positive in the fourth quadrant.

This is commonly known as the ``CAST rule," but this text prefers to refer to it as the \textbf{ASTC chart}, because of two reasons. First, ASTC is in an order that also helps the student remember the order of the quadrants, while CAST starts in the fourth quadrant. Second, ASTC can be remembered with the acronym ``All Scholars Take Calculus."

\subsection{Special Triangles}

In this section, we will only look at non-right angles that can exist in a right triangle; these angles are acute.

Here are two triangles that are extremely important to trigonometry: the \(45-45-90\) triangle and the \(30-60-90\) triangle.

\begin{center}
%\begin{comment}
\begin{tikzpicture}[baseline=(current bounding box.center)]
\coordinate (A) at (0,0);
\coordinate (B) at (4,4);
\coordinate (C) at (4,0);
\draw (A) -- node[above left] {\(\sqrt{2}\)} (B) -- node[right] {\(1\)} (C) -- node[below] {\(1\)} (A);
\path pic[draw,angle radius=7.5mm,"\(45^\circ\)",angle eccentricity=1.6] {angle = C--A--B};
\path pic[draw,angle radius=7.5mm,"\(45^\circ\)",angle eccentricity=1.6] {angle = A--B--C};
\draw ($(C)!3mm!(B)$) -| ($(C)!3mm!(A)$);
\end{tikzpicture}
\hspace{6em}
\begin{tikzpicture}[baseline=(current bounding box.center)]
\coordinate (A) at (0,0);
\coordinate (B) at (4,2.309);
\coordinate (C) at (4,0);
\draw (A) -- node[above left] {\(2\)} (B) -- node[right] {\(1\)} (C) -- node[below] {\(\sqrt{3}\)} (A);
\path pic[draw,angle radius=9mm,"\(30^\circ\)",angle eccentricity=1.6] {angle = C--A--B};
\path pic[draw,angle radius=6mm,"\(60^\circ\)",angle eccentricity=1.6] {angle = A--B--C};
\draw ($(C)!3mm!(B)$) -| ($(C)!3mm!(A)$);
\end{tikzpicture}
%\end{comment}
\end{center}

Let's take a look at the values of the trigonometric functions in terms of the angles in the bottom left. Label these angles as \(\theta,\) and label each side of the triangle as ``opposite," ``adjacent," or ``hypotenuse."
\begin{center}
%\begin{comment}
\begin{tikzpicture}
\coordinate (A) at (0,0);
\coordinate (B) at (4,3);
\coordinate (C) at (4,0);
\draw (A) -- node[above,sloped] {Hypotenuse} (B) -- node[below,sloped,rotate=180] {Opposite} (C) -- node[below] {Adjacent} (A);
\path pic[draw,angle radius=7.5mm,"\(\theta\)",angle eccentricity=1.6] {angle = C--A--B};
\draw ($(C)!3mm!(B)$) -| ($(C)!3mm!(A)$);
\end{tikzpicture}
%\end{comment}
\end{center}

\example Using the above triangles, fill in the following table.

\begin{center}
\renewcommand*{\arraystretch}{1.3}
\begin{tabular}{|c|>{\xstrut}c|c|c|}
\hline
\(\theta\) (Deg.) & \(30^\circ\) & \(45^\circ\) & \(60^\circ\) \\ \hline
\(\theta\) (Rad.) & \(\frac{\pi}{6}\) & \(\frac{\pi}{4}\) & \(\frac{\pi}{3}\) \\ \hline
\(\sin\theta\) & & & \\ \hline
\(\cos\theta\) & & & \\ \hline
\(\tan\theta\) & & & \\ \hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}
\solution\\

\begin{center}
\renewcommand*{\arraystretch}{1.3}
\begin{tabular}{|c|>{\xstrut}c|c|c|}
\hline
\(\theta\) (Deg.) & \(30^\circ\) & \(45^\circ\) & \(60^\circ\) \\ \hline
\(\theta\) (Rad.) & \(\frac{\pi}{6}\) & \(\frac{\pi}{4}\) & \(\frac{\pi}{3}\) \\ \hline
\(\sin\theta\) & \(\frac{1}{2}\) & \(\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}\) & \(\frac{1}{2}\) \\ \hline
\(\cos\theta\) & \(\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}\) & \(\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}\) & \(\frac{1}{2}\) \\ \hline
\(\tan\theta\) & \(\frac{\sqrt{3}}{3}\) & \(1\) & \(\sqrt{3}\) \\ \hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

From this chart, we can construct a comprehensive unit circle.\\

\noindent \figurelabel

\begin{center}
%%\begin{comment}
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=5,cap=round,>=latex]
\draw[->] (-1.5cm,0cm) -- (1.5cm,0cm) node[right,fill=white] {\(x\)};
\draw[->] (0cm,-1.5cm) -- (0cm,1.5cm) node[above,fill=white] {\(y\)};

\draw[thick] (0cm,0cm) circle(1cm);

\foreach \x in {0,30,45,60,90,120,135,150,180,210,225,240,270,300,315,330} {
\draw[black] (0cm,0cm)--(\x:1cm);
\filldraw[black](\x:1cm) circle(0.4pt);
\draw(\x:0.6cm) node[fill=white] {\(\x^\circ\)};
}

\foreach \x/\xtext in {
0/0,
30/\frac{\pi}{6},
45/\frac{\pi}{4},
60/\frac{\pi}{3},
90/\frac{\pi}{2},
120/\frac{2\pi}{3},
135/\frac{3\pi}{4},
150/\frac{5\pi}{6},
180/\pi,
210/\frac{7\pi}{6},
225/\frac{5\pi}{4},
240/\frac{4\pi}{3},
270/\frac{3\pi}{2},
300/\frac{5\pi}{3},
315/\frac{7\pi}{4},
330/\frac{11\pi}{6}
}
\draw (\x:0.85cm) node[fill=white] {\(\xtext\)};

\foreach \x/\xtext/\y in {
30/\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}/\frac{1}{2},
45/\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}/\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2},
60/\frac{1}{2}/\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2},
120/-\frac{1}{2}/\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2},
135/-\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}/\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2},
150/-\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}/\frac{\sqrt{1}}{2},
210/-\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}/-\frac{1}{2},
225/-\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}/-\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2},
240/-\frac{1}{2}/-\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2},
300/\frac{1}{2}/-\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2},
315/\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}/-\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2},
330/\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}/-\frac{1}{2}}
\draw(\x:1.3cm) node[fill=white] {\(\left(\xtext,\y\right)\)};

\draw(-1.15cm,0cm) node[above=1pt] {\((-1,0)\)};
\draw(1.15cm,0cm)  node[above=1pt] {\((1,0)\)};
\draw(0cm,-1.15cm) node[fill=white] {\((0,-1)\)};
\draw(0cm,1.15cm)  node[fill=white] {\((0,1)\)};
\end{tikzpicture}
%%\end{comment}
\end{center}

It is extremely important to comprehensively understand the steps in creating this unit circle. It is highly recommended to print out a blank copy of the unit circle and practice filling in the values shown above.

